9:T6e9,<p>An agentic organization is one built around the assumption that intelligence is abundant and coordination is scarce.</p>
<p>This is the opposite of how most companies are built today, where intelligence (human time and attention) is the primary constraint.</p>
<h2>What it implies</h2>
<p><strong>Fewer humans, higher leverage.</strong> Each person in an agentic org is a system architect, not an executor. Their job is to design and steward workflows, not run them.</p>
<p><strong>Memory infrastructure matters.</strong> In a human org, context lives in people's heads. People leave, and the context goes with them. Agentic orgs need explicit memory systems — documented decisions, structured context, institutional knowledge that outlives any individual.</p>
<p><strong>Speed compounds.</strong> If you can run 10x more experiments with the same team, you learn 10x faster. The compounding effect of this over 2-3 years is enormous.</p>
<h2>The coordination problem</h2>
<p>Agents are bad at coordination with other agents unless the interfaces are designed carefully. This is where humans stay essential — not as doers, but as designers.</p>
<p>Who decides what the agents work on? Who handles the edge cases? Who monitors for failure modes?</p>
<p>These are human jobs for the foreseeable future.</p>
<h2>Where we're at</h2>
<p>Most "AI-first" companies are actually just human companies with AI tools. They've automated some tasks but haven't changed the organizational structure.</p>
<p>True agentic orgs are rare. But they're coming. And they'll have an operating advantage that looks like an unfair one.</p>
<p>See also: <a href="/notes/systems-thinking" class="wikilink">Systems Thinking</a>, <a href="/notes/leverage" class="wikilink">Leverage</a></p>
